Durban -The DA-led uMngeni Municipality has set aside millions of rand to fix potholes, deal with refuse disposal and to fix street lights.The municipality tabled its adjustment budget on Monday.Mayor Chris Pappas said: “We are pleased to announce that although we face constrained financial conditions as a municipality, we have managed to adjust and appropriate additional amounts for capital service delivery projects for the second half of the financial year (ending 30 June).”He said R4 million will go towards roads maintenance (potholes), R2.45 million towards a refuse compactor and R1.2 million for plant equipment for the dump site.Pappas said R300 000 has been allocated for brush cutters and grass cutting equipment, R200 000 for a mobile fines collection machine and R1 million for street lights.MORE ON THISuMngeni Municipality to adopt aggressive tactics to collect debt from residents‘Travel local’ urges uMngeni mayor as KZN Midlands sets its sights on more tourism spendMixed reactions from councillors after Msunduzi municipal boss resignsThe municipality has also set aside R250 000 for uniforms, specialised safety wear and tools of the trade, R200 000 for a pedestrian roller to repair potholes.He said revenue was also looking up for the municipality, and that there has been an increase in the collection rate of the municipality with a R2.5 million improvement in January, while February is looking to be much better.“An increased allocation was made to bulk purchases to ensure that we stay up to date with Eskom. An increased amount was allocated towards legal costs to fight cases involving corruption and mismanagement as well as to take action that supports the municipality.“We will continue to work hard to put basic service delivery first and root out the ghosts of corruption and mismanagement that linger in the system,” he said.THE MERCURY